<h2>Bagnasco, resignation? I think there is no reason to hypothesize it
On the news of possible resignation of Pope Francis,» Cardinal Angelo Bagnasco at Rtl 102.5 > answered: "I don't know that, but I think there's no reason to talk about resignation or to hypothesize them. If the world stopped to pray, it is a great thing: a chain of prayer > which rose to the Lord precisely for the Holy Father Francis at this delicate moment."
"According to medical bulletins, the Pope's health conditions are slightly improved.> We continue to pray that it will improve more and more, until complete healing and return to his ministry."
"The whole world, all those who in one way or another participated in this moment of prayer with the rosary, will bring in the heart this experience, which will help to live and to be together better than before. This moment will be repeated, and the continuity of this prayer in the square is another very beautiful sign > and important sign of faith in Jesus and of union around the successor of Peter, the Holy Father Francis. This certainly strengthens our faith and our ecclesial communion >" he concluded.
